  "prompt": "Is gold a Non Performing Asset?",
  "response": "Gold itself is not typically classified as a Non-Performing Asset (NPA). Here's a brief explanation:\n\n1. Non-Performing Asset (NPA):\n- A term used primarily in banking and finance\n- Refers to loans or advances that are in default or are not generating income for the lender\n- Usually applies to loans where principal or interest payments are overdue\n\n2. Gold:\n- Is considered an asset or investment\n- Can be held in various forms (physical gold, gold ETFs, gold bonds)\n- Generally viewed as a store of value or investment instrument\n- Does not generate regular income like loans or bonds, but can appreciate in value\n\n3. When Gold Might Be Related to NPAs:\n- If a loan is taken against gold as collateral and the borrower defaults\n- The gold used as security could then be part of the NPA process\n- But the gold itself is not an NPA\n\n4. Gold as an Investment:\n- Can be considered a passive asset\n- Potential for capital appreciation\n- Serves as a hedge against inflation and economic uncertainty\n\nIn summary, gold is an asset or investment, not a Non-Performing Asset in the traditional banking sense.",
